U.S.: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the most foolish.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it proved to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the same text used several times as in Iraq, but it also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement for its own statement: “A new way forward.”
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as “an irresponsible and catastrophic decision.”
The following months, however, proved that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today nothing about Iraq is talked about in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, but it objectively left his successor in a much more favourable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to repeat itself.
Field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of Afghan Operation General Stanley McCristal, who, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided gunmen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president wavered for three months, but he didn’t think of anything better, so at least he tricked the general over 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself had previously counted at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is fulfilled.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin, after which patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “capable of action,” a minimum goal of the whole operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy clashes with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, can believe that the military sent to war to “go home soon,” will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect statement of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the Hindu Kush war.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of the troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that three years are missing for the presidential election and therefore there is still much time left to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
