A Czech Discovery: An Effective Substance Even in 'Calched' HIV Viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists makes tests for new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some already accessible drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured so far.
However, the life of patients can be significantly prolonged thanks to a mixture of drugs that prevent replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metallocarbonates have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbonates are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way different from all the drugs used today, and therefore can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus’s albumin.
Metal carbonates have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed of the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitorous and resilient virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, there is no fragmentation of the HIV virus and no mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see the table) are joined by a short organic series, which is still being systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was carried out in sample, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metallocarbonates on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, in which drugs often do not work.
The mechanism of the unique effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications does, that metallocarbonates are interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Molequia Institute <0xC5><0x98>ez<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8D>ov<0xC3><0xA1>, Biophysics Institution and Genetics Department of Genetics in the Institute of Structural Biology.
