Management Revolution or the End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees recalls the position of the companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is that the collaborators adhere to "values" determined from above as previously it was about imposing to consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to the strategies of conquest of the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to the factors of preference of the customers is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can result in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more so, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) “requires all parties involved (...) to have proactive behavior and a prospective vision”; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that completely opposes the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as Orange’s questionnaire among its employees, incentivize the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behaviorist theory that American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind them.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the “commands” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms executives in a mechanistic management stance, unsuitable for today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies involves adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, engagement with the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only the studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of the motivations of employees.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, company managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resource management "on the spot".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
