The Cradle of the Dinosaur
The Tawa findae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran over the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with lance-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would not have been anything special.
But the Tawa findae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes, we’ve found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were collected in total.
Finding Confirms Theories About the Ancient History of Dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi Indian sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other experts in dinosaurs do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, for example, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the older fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the avocados pelsaurus, the quadrupedal sauropods with the herbians known as the "long neck" and their paris.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa findae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt comments.
For example, in the skull of Tawa, researchers found traces of air pockets, such as those also owned by theropod descendants, the birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breath of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa, the bones of the spine were also evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the later giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At Least Three Waves of Migrants to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers deduce that saurians first emerged there.
Therefore, the three genealogical lineages were separated at first and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single terrestrial mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawae find the remains of two other not very closely related theropods.
The three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three migratory waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are opponents too.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of modern crocodiles and pterosaurs and many other sauries.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded around the world and developed many new species, while the kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary towards the Jurassic.
Successful stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
