His body is two-dimensional and scandalously colored.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red cheeks like blood, deformed, smearing teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy and flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Sparkling and malignant voices resound from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand them, voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls out two stereo cables, ties them to form a hanging knot, and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
It rises in a mouthpiece and puts the knot around the neck.
- Jump.
The rope is loosened.
What a lesson for you!, the voices shout in a choir that turns the timpani, "Come to the clinic and get healed!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that caused it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizophrenic-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, taking medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, for three years he is married.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside, and they fall into a state of over-excitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecution mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis opens the door to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
Perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the general psychiatric clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time, he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, awakening, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, “the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it should be.”
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still an unknown why our brain makes cabriolets.
According to Fuchs, states of exception can lead anyone to temporarily lose contact with reality.
But not everyone develops a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes, there are also other determining factors.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the brain’s neuronal maturity is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a mother’s viral disease during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains an unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a previous disposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmitting system.
When the brain warms up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive medications to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says Lübeck professor of psychology Erich Kasten.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or does not often depend on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die unreale Welt in unserem Kopf, published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with psychic disorders such as personality limit disorder or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and cranial trauma.
Surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer from hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memories that are usually suppressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or are poorly inhibited; when our brain is heated, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or a psychosis.
But also restriction of stimuli, stress, bad love or other brain states of exception.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having experienced hallucinations at least once in their lifetime.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
If it wasn't for those pictures and voices.
Sometimes, during recreation, it happens that a dull boy with long dark hair directs the word to him.
When she answers, the other students look at her surprised; no one but her hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a little strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she's not dreaming.
She is awake and comes and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the next bench.
You may even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, he likes the guy.
Sometimes you wonder if you’re crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class sometimes he cannot follow the lesson because the teacher – to his eyes and ears – is presenting a new companion, while for the rest he explains the mathematical equations in a visible and audible way.
At night, apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for the sleep to arrive, which often comes late and is scarce, he does not know whether he is awake or dreaming, whether the images he sees, the cheeks or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs, appear in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he yells at the figures.
He hasn't told his parents and friends anything, they'd think he's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations disappeared.
Since she has come into contact over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, she knows she’s not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art by desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while they will begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is out of work and is in charge of looking for entertainment.
Sarah K., only daughter, was little afraid of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he calls dad since he uses reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," Kasten says, " takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies nocturnal fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that patients appreciate their hallucinations as a special skill.
The boundary between sleep and hallucination
In this overly conscious world, imaginary experiences usually pathologize, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also entails something positive and creative – madness is a work of desperation.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that can subsequently not differentiate from being awake.
Dream conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis being fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein erleben eine motorische Lähmung.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of himself or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a self-imaginary world that is decoupled from reality.
A form of situation boundary between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to a situation in itself that our own ability to create allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also the art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as an action to save the soul.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on several-day trips after a heart valve surgery with a heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen dived into a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he was seen lying in bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot was watching over his health.
It was seen in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek man on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed his hospital bed in the Alps with firn snow and met a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, thus describing your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intense even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations, and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Each modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
