75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and work trajectory of women in Spain', developed by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the start of coexistence in a couple and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an out-of-home activity, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start cohabitation as a couple earlier, advance first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and maternity, and have fewer offspring.
“Women aged 35 to 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with a fixed job have needed more time to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on maternity, albeit less on the timing of mating,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they get married and when they have the first stem.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at which they marry and have the first child.
The difference is also maintained between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who have elementary and higher studies have been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average respectively.
“There is also another division among women based on their level of study.
While those who have elementary studies get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those at middle or higher levels invest in this sequence and give priority to getting a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child,” Delgado says.
