Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory.
As with ABS anti-lock brakes and ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all new registered cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of deficiency is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, although, because of their way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions within range.
The emergency braking assistant does what it does is to increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the pistol that the driver gives.
But it does not always hold that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by car component manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers involved in an accident had not come to the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum to the braking system, reducing the distance that the car uses in stopping.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with these types of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented per year.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided – when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or camera) detects obstacles and alerts the driver, in addition to acting lightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
