New Tools for Periting Cars
In these days of temporary and accidents, not only car workshops win.
Every day thousands of cars that have suffered a disaster are towed to a workshop, where an expert must assess the damage suffered and what the repair cost will be.
No sinister is the same, and calculating part costs and labor time can be a long and complicated job.
Manually calculating the cost of a repair of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including parts and workmanship, can take two or three hours.
Instead, with the support of the latest computer tools would be a matter of minutes
That’s why almost 100% of experts use these types of systems.
Service providers and solutions for damage assessment and maintenance are dedicated to collecting the information supplied by manufacturers, and then developing it and offering it to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, from the American group Solera, is the leading firm; 80% of the ratings are made with its products.
The other firms competing in the field of valuation and information-making tools on the sector are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data supplied by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Vel<0xC3><0xA1>zquez, Sales Director of Audatex, in Spain they work with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with the information in different formats.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, to the extent that more versions, variants and engines have been released in the last five years than in the previous fifteen.
As soon as a new car enters the market, these companies start to work.
It is a very hard work, because you have to catalog each of the thousands of parts of the vehicle and enter their price.
In addition, from each model is made a "smart" graphic image where you can "paint" different parts of tourism.
If it’s a windscreen model, the work can be done in a week if the process goes too fast.
If it is a minority car, it may take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information about 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models have information about Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini, for example.
As for the mobile park that circulates, they exceed 99%.
To do the documentation work and the elaboration of the databases, Audatex has eight centers spread around the world (Spain, France, Germany, USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters is in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics experts) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>90 million annually in developing these databases.
2.5 million data are included every month, and customers receive updates every two days.
The elaboration of this huge flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer various products.
The most frequent use focuses on repair and maintenance, but depending on which countries there are also tools for the management of detachment parts or to calculate the venal or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used ones in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but in the United States.
In view of the products offered by Audatex it is easy to get an idea of the type of support they can provide to professionals in the sector.
This company offers ten different tools, the star product AudaPlus, the standard accident assessment solution, intended for experts.
It includes cars, motorcycles and light or heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the estimated repair times by the manufacturer or the paint bars.
This tool is paid according to usage, for each valuation.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, a maximum of ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which conducts thousands of expertise, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the full identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it exited the assembly line only with its frame number.
